Statistical infernces on Titanic Dataset

Observation- 1

Null hypothesis: The median fare of a passenger is about $14USD
Alternate hypothesis: The median fare of a passenger is greater than $14USD
# Visualizing the distribution of data
hist(titanic_isi$fare)

# Generate 1000 bootstrap samples centered at null

titanic_hyp_faretest <- titanic_isi %>%
  filter(!is.na(fare)) %>%
  specify(response = fare) %>%
  hypothesize(null = "point",med=14) %>%
  generate(reps = 1000,type = "bootstrap") %>%
  calculate(stat="median")

# Calculate observed mean
fare_med_obs <- titanic_isi%>%
  summarize(median(fare,na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  # Extract numerical value
  pull() 

# # Calculate P-value
titanic_hyp_faretest %>%
  filter(stat > fare_med_obs) %>%
  summarize(n() / 1000)
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   `n()/1000`
##        <dbl>
## 1      0.161
# Visualization

titnanic_vis1 <- titanic_hyp_faretest %>% visualize()

titnanic_vis1 +  geom_vline(color = "red", xintercept = fare_med_obs)

P value caluclated is higher than significance level 0.05, hence we fail reject the null hypothesis.

Observation- 2

Null hypothesis: The avg age of a passenger is about 30yrs
Alternate hypothesis: The avg age of a passenger is more than 30yrs
# Visualizing the distribution of data

hist(titanic_isi$age)

# Generate 1000 bootstrap samples centered at null

titanic_hyp_agetest <- titanic_isi %>%
  filter(!is.na(age)) %>%
  specify(response = age) %>%
  hypothesize(null = "point",mu=30) %>%
  generate(reps = 1000,type = "bootstrap") %>%
  calculate(stat="mean")

# Calculate observed mean
age_med_obs <- titanic_isi%>%
  summarize(mean(age,na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  # Extract numerical value
  pull() 

# Calculate P-Value
titanic_hyp_agetest %>%
  filter(stat > age_med_obs) %>%
  summarize(n() / 1000)
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   `n()/1000`
##        <dbl>
## 1        0.6
# Determine critical value
t_star <- qt(0.975, df = nrow(titanic_isi) - 1)

# Calculate the 95% CI via standard error method

titanic_hyp_agetest %>%
  summarize(boot_se = sd(titanic_hyp_agetest$stat)) %>%
  summarize(l = age_med_obs - t_star * boot_se,
            u = age_med_obs + t_star * boot_se)
## # A tibble: 1 x 2
##          l        u
##      <dbl>    <dbl>
## 1 29.00243 30.75984
# Visualization 

ggplot(titanic_hyp_agetest, aes(x = stat)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 30, color = "white") +  geom_vline(color = "red", xintercept = age_med_obs)

P value caluclated is higher than significance level 0.05, hence we fail reject the null hypothesis.

We see that 30 is contained in this confidence interval as a plausible value of μ(the unknown population mean) and .This matches with our hypothesis test results of failing to reject the null hypothesis

Observation- 3

Null hypothesis: The avg age of male and female passangers are the same
Alternate hypothesis: there is a diffence in the avg age of male/female passangers
# Generate 1000 differences in means via randomization
titanic_hyp_group_gen <- titanic_isi %>% 
  filter(!is.na(sex),!is.na(age)) %>%
  specify(age ~ sex) %>% 
  # Null = no difference between means
  hypothesize(null = "independence") %>% 
  # Shuffle labels 1000 times
  generate(reps = 1000, type = "permute") %>%
  # Calculate test statistic
  calculate(stat = "diff in means", order = c("male","female"))           

#  Calulcate diff in observed means
titanic_dif_mean <- titanic_isi%>%
  group_by(sex) %>%
  summarize(mean_age = mean(age,na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  # Extract
  pull() %>%
  # Calculate difference
  diff() 

# Calculate p-value
titanic_hyp_group_gen %>%
  # Identify simulated test statistics at least as extreme as observed
  filter(stat < titanic_dif_mean) %>%
  # Calculate p-value
  summarize(p_val = (n() / 1000)) %>%
  pull()
## [1] 0.98
# Visualization

titanic_vis <- titanic_hyp_group_gen %>% visualize()

titanic_vis + geom_vline(aes(xintercept=titanic_dif_mean),col="red") + geom_vline(aes(xintercept=-titanic_dif_mean),col="red")

P value caluclated is higher than significance level 0.05, hence we fail reject the null hypothesis.

  calculate(stat = "diff in means", order = c("0","1"))

cancer_dif_mean <- cancer_isi%>%
  group_by(TRT) %>%
  summarize(mean_age = mean(AGE,na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  # Extract
  pull() %>%
  # Calculate difference
  diff() 

# Calculate p-value
cancer_hyp_trt %>%
  # Identify simulated test statistics at least as extreme as observed
  filter(stat < cancer_dif_mean) %>%
  # Calculate p-value
  summarize(p_val = (n() / 1000)) %>%
  pull()
## [1] 0.495
# Visualization - 

cancer_trt_vis <- cancer_hyp_trt %>% visualize()

cancer_trt_vis + geom_vline(aes(xintercept=cancer_dif_mean),col="red") + geom_vline(aes(xintercept=-cancer_dif_mean),col="red")

ggplot(cancer_isi,aes(TRT,AGE)) + geom_boxplot() + coord_flip()

P value caluclated higher than significance level 0.05, hence we fail to reject the null hypothesis

Alternate hypothesis: The avg weights aren’t the same for treatement and non-treatment patients
# Generate 1000 differences in means via randomization
cancer_hyp_trt_weight<- cancer_isi %>% 
  filter(!is.na(TRT),!is.na(WEIGHIN)) %>%
  specify(WEIGHIN ~ TRT) %>% 
  # Null = no difference between means
  hypothesize(null = "independence") %>% 
  # Shuffle labels 1000 times
  generate(reps = 1000, type = "permute") %>%
  # Calculate test statistic
  calculate(stat = "diff in means", order = c("0","1"))

Introduction to statistical learning

Statistical learning refers to a vast set of tools for understanding data. these tools can be classified as below

  • Supervised

  • Unsupervised

Supervised Learning

The majority of practical machine learning uses supervised learning.

Supervised learning is where you have input variables (x) and an output variable (Y) and you use an algorithm to learn the mapping function from the input to the output.

Y = f(X)

The goal is to approximate the mapping function so well that when you have new input data (x) that you can predict the output variables (Y) for that data.

It is called supervised learning because the process of an algorithm learning from the training dataset can be thought of as a teacher supervising the learning process. We know the correct answers, the algorithm iteratively makes predictions on the training data and is corrected by the teacher. Learning stops when the algorithm achieves an acceptable level of performance.

Supervised learning problems can be further grouped into regression and classification problems.

Classification: A classification problem is when the output variable is a category, such as “red” or “blue” or “disease” and “no disease”.

Regression: A regression problem is when the output variable is a real value, such as “dollars” or “weight”.

Some common types of problems built on top of classification and regression include recommendation and time series prediction respectively.

Some popular examples of supervised machine learning algorithms are:

  1. Linear regression for regression problems.

  2. Random forest for classification and regression problems.

  3. Support vector machines for classification problems.

Unsupervised Learning

Unsupervised learning is where you only have input data (X) and no corresponding output variables.

The goal for unsupervised learning is to model the underlying structure or distribution in the data in order to learn more about the data.

These are called unsupervised learning because unlike supervised learning above there is no correct answers and there is no teacher. Algorithms are left to their own devises to discover and present the interesting structure in the data.

Unsupervised learning problems can be further grouped into clustering and association problems.

Clustering: A clustering problem is where you want to discover the inherent groupings in the data, such as grouping customers by purchasing behavior.

Association: An association rule learning problem is where you want to discover rules that describe large portions of your data, such as people that buy X also tend to buy Y.

Some popular examples of unsupervised learning algorithms are:

  1. k-means for clustering problems.
  2. Apriori algorithm for association rule learning problems.
